You’ve probably shipped a useState hook and a useEffect to solve a problem CSS can now handle in one line. Not because you're behind — because these features landed quietly, browser support caught up fast, and nobody sent a memo.
Here are seven CSS capabilities that are production-ready right now, each solving a problem you’ve probably reached for JavaScript to fix.

1. :has() — The Parent Selector We Waited 20 Years For
CSS never let you style a parent based on its children. Until now.
/* Style a form group only if it contains an invalid input */
.form-group:has(input:invalid) {
border-color: crimson;
background: #fff5f5;
}/* Style a card differently if it has an image */
.card:has(img) {
grid-template-rows: auto 1fr;
}/* Hide an empty section entirely — no conditional rendering needed */
section:has(> .content:empty) {
display: none;
}Where this saves you real work: conditional styling that used to require a class toggle in JS (hasImage, isInvalid, isEmpty) now lives entirely in CSS. Fewer re-renders, fewer state variables, less to test.

2. Container Queries — Components That Respond to Their Box, Not the Viewport
Media queries ask “how wide is the screen?” Container queries ask “how wide is this component’s parent?” — which is almost always the question you actually meant to ask.
.card-container {
container-type: inline-size;
container-name: card;
}@container card (min-width: 400px) {
.card {
grid-template-columns: 120px 1fr;
}
}Drop the same card component into a narrow sidebar or a wide main column, and it adapts to its own space — not the browser window. This is the missing piece for truly reusable design-system components.

3. @property — Give Custom Properties an Actual Type
CSS variables are normally just strings. @property lets you register one with a real type, a syntax, and a default — which unlocks smooth animation of things that were previously all-or-nothing.
@property --gradient-angle {
syntax: '<angle>';
inherits: false;
initial-value: 0deg;
}.button {
background: conic-gradient(from var(--gradient-angle), #ff5f6d, #ffc371, #ff5f6d);
transition: --gradient-angle 0.4s ease;
}.button:hover {
--gradient-angle: 360deg;
}Without @property, browsers can't interpolate that angle — it just snaps. With it, you get a buttery gradient rotation with zero JavaScript and zero animation library.

4. color-mix() — Stop Hardcoding Tint/Shade Variants
Every design system ends up with a pile of manually-picked color variants: primary-100, primary-200, hover states, disabled states. color-mix() generates them on the fly.
:root {
--primary: #5b5fef;
}.button:hover {
background: color-mix(in srgb, var(--primary) 85%, white);
}.button:disabled {
background: color-mix(in srgb, var(--primary) 40%, gray);
}One source-of-truth color, infinite derived states, no Sass functions, no build step.

5. text-wrap: balance — The End of Ugly Widowed Headlines
That one word hanging alone on the last line of a heading has bothered every frontend dev in history. This fixes it in one declaration.
h1, h2, h3 {
text-wrap: balance;
}p {
text-wrap: pretty; /* avoids widows in body copy too */
}The browser redistributes line breaks so text wraps evenly. No more manual <br> tags or JS libraries just to make a headline look intentional.

6. Scroll-Driven Animations — Animate on Scroll, No JS, No Jank
Scroll-linked effects used to mean an IntersectionObserver, a scroll listener, and a requestAnimationFrame loop — running on the main thread, fighting for frames. Now the browser's compositor does it natively.
@keyframes fade-in-up {
from {
opacity: 0;
transform: translateY(40px);
}
to {
opacity: 1;
transform: translateY(0);
}
}.reveal {
animation: fade-in-up linear both;
animation-timeline: view();
animation-range: entry 0% cover 40%;
}This runs off the main thread, so it stays smooth even during heavy JS execution — something your old scroll-listener version almost certainly couldn’t promise.

7. subgrid — Finally, Nested Grids That Actually Align
Nested grid layouts have always fought each other — a card’s internal grid never lines up with its siblings’ internal grids. subgrid lets a nested grid inherit its parent's tracks.
.card-list {
display: grid;
grid-template-columns: 1fr;
grid-template-rows: auto auto auto;
gap: 1rem;
}.card {
display: grid;
grid-row: span 3;
grid-template-rows: subgrid;
}Now every card’s title, body, and footer align perfectly across the whole row — even with wildly different content lengths. This used to require JS height-matching hacks.

Try This Before You Reach for a Library
Next time you’re about to install a dependency or write a useEffect for something visual — conditional styling, responsive components, color variants, scroll effects, layout alignment — check whether CSS already does it. Browser support for all seven of these is solid in current versions of Chrome, Edge, Firefox, and Safari as of 2026.
Less JavaScript. Fewer re-renders. Smaller bundles. Sometimes the most unique move is just using the platform.
